Time Series Analysis of Fatal Police Shootings

Brendan Graham

January 15, 2016

Introduction

Data Description

The fatal police shooting data is from an ongoing project developed by The Washington Post, which has been keeping track of fatal police shootings using news reports, public records, Internet databases and original reporting. The database tracks shootings in which a police officer, while on duty, shot and killed a civilian and does not include deaths of people in custody, fatal shootings by off-duty officers or deaths in which police gunfire did not kill the individual. The Post’s database is updated regularly on their GitHub page as new fatal shootings are reported and as new facts emerge about individual cases. In addition to the date and location of a fatal shooting, the database also tracks variables such as race, gender, age and signs of any mental illness exhibited by the victim.

The data consists of fatal police shootings in the U.S. between 2015-01-01 and 2016-02-12 and contains 1130 observations of 19 variables. The initial data set contained 1130 observations of only 12 variables: ID, victim’s name, date of the shooting, manner of death, what the victim was armed with (if anything), age, gender, race, city, state, if the victim showed signs of mental illness, and threat level at the time of the shooting. By definition, the data set did not include days where there were 0 fatal police shootings. To make the data complete, I filled in those date “gaps” so there would be an observation for every day, regardless of whether or not a fatal police shooting had occured. To account for this, I added a column called “count” (i.e. the number of victims) which took on a value of either 1 or 0 for each observation, thus preserving the initial total number of fatal police shootings.

I also added the following variables: year, month, day, number of victims,1 and current population estimate for each city in the data set2. I also grouped the race variable into 4 categories (Black, Hispanic, Other, White) and grouped age into 5 categories (18 to 29, 30 to 44, 45 and Older, Under 18, Unknown).

The mean number of fatal police shootings per day in the data is 0.93 with a standard deviation of 0.25. The tables below show the total number of daily fatal police shootings by race, by age category, and presence of a weapon. Most victims of fatal police shootings were White (549 White victims vs. 280 Black victims) and between the age of 30 to 44. Most victims were armed with a gun at the time of the shooting and their threat level was reported as “attack”. In terms of location, most fatal police shootings occured in Los Angeles with 16 shootings, followed by Houston and Las Vegas, each with11 shootings. However, NM, WY and OK had the most fatal police shootings per 100,000 residents.

The monthly bar plot below shows peaks of fatal shootings in May, July and December 2015. Below that, the timeseries plot shows a fairly consistent spread around a mean of 2.72 fatal police shootings per day.

A plot of the auto correlation function (ACF) shows not much seasonality in the data.
